And here are your hosts.

00:44.140 --> 00:45.420
This is Daryl Lane.

00:45.520 --> 00:46.200
And Bill Vernon.

00:46.760 --> 00:49.040
James Gunn approaches science fiction from many angles.

00:49.540 --> 00:54.600
He writes it, he teaches it, and he's published important historical and critical material in science fiction.

00:54.600 --> 01:00.920
Some of Gunn's better known novels include The Joymakers, The Immortals, The Listeners, and The Dreamers.

01:01.380 --> 01:05.480
The Immortals was the basis for the television show of a few years back, The Immortal.

01:06.120 --> 01:15.520
Gunn's critical work, in addition to numerous essays, consists of two major publications, Alternate Worlds, a 1975 history of science fiction, and The Road to Science Fiction,

01:15.720 --> 01:20.860
a four volume anthology that includes Gunn's essays on the definition of science fiction and its historical development.

01:20.860 --> 01:28.980
Gunn's criticism is valuable because it not only comes from someone who knows the field, but also because Gunn is a scholar and professor at a major university.

01:29.380 --> 01:32.340
He brings the insight of a professional academic to the field.

01:32.780 --> 01:36.520
We talked with Gunn about how he divides himself between being both a writer and a teacher.

01:37.120 --> 01:39.820
We asked him if he'd ever considered writing as a full-time career.

01:39.820 --> 02:01.040
I did, as a matter of fact, write full-time for a period of a little more than three years, a year in 1948-49, and I went back to school then and got a master's degree, but I continued to write.

02:03.940 --> 02:18.380
Then, after I'd worked for this paperback publisher, after I got my master's degree, worked for a paperback publisher for a year and a half, I found out that I'd sold four stories that I hadn't known about and decided to go back to full-time writing.

02:18.380 --> 02:48.360
So I did write full-time from the fall of 1942 until the late summer of 1955, and really much of the groundwork for the later books that I published and the success that I had, I think, such as it was, was based upon that freelance paper.

02:48.380 --> 03:09.860
I didn't make a lot of money out of it, you know, below the poverty level, but my needs were fairly simple at that time and what it later paid off in the sense that the stories that I wrote appeared in books and some of them even were made in the movies and all that sort of thing.

03:10.740 --> 03:13.160
Gunn explains how I became involved in teaching.

03:13.160 --> 03:39.140
It was after 1955, or in the fall of 1955, after my wife and I had moved back to Lawrence, Kansas, simply as a place to live, but I got involved almost by accident with teaching at the university from which I'd gotten my two degrees, University of Kansas, and became involved with other aspects of the university.

03:39.140 --> 03:53.880
I edited the alumni magazine for three years and then became director of public relations for the university for 12 years before returning to full-time teaching and writing in 1970.

03:54.600 --> 03:57.120
Gunn had always intended to write science fiction criticism.

03:57.940 --> 04:11.900
But looking back upon it, I know, I think right from the beginning, I had the feeling that I wanted to do criticism in the area.

04:12.840 --> 04:39.140
My first 10 stories, for instance, were published under a pseudonym of Edwin James using, I began to use my own name with the 11th story, but the reason I can remember now for doing that was the fact that I thought I would write criticism about science fiction and I wanted to save my real name for that.

04:39.900 --> 04:47.660
But after 10 stories, I decided that was foolish and I ought to use my real name for everything.

04:48.820 --> 04:57.060
And that looking back upon it, I think the academic interest was there right from the beginning.

04:57.920 --> 05:03.200
Beginning next time, we'll talk with James Gunn about his writing, both the stories and the criticism.

