James Gunn, author, critic and teacher of science fiction, has written some valuable books on the definition and historical development of science fiction.

06:51.500 --> 06:58.940
He's examining some big questions in this work, things like what is science fiction, what makes it different from other literature and where it comes from.

06:58.940 --> 07:09.800
And since Gunn is a professor at the University of Kansas, besides being a long-time author of science fiction, he combines a scholar's objectivity and a creator's understanding in answering these questions.

07:10.500 --> 07:16.000
Alternate Worlds, published in 1976, is his first major critical work. Gunn explains its origin.

07:28.940 --> 07:34.080
I'm a writer at the University of Kansas, and I'm a writer at the University of Kansas, where there is some resistance to the notion of doing that.

07:35.100 --> 07:47.680
And I accepted because I had the feeling that there wasn't a good history of science fiction, and that this course would give me the incentive to write it.

07:48.680 --> 08:04.640
So I sat down and wrote very fast, and ended up with 13 chapters representing about 13 lectures for the 14-week semester.

08:06.560 --> 08:27.000
And these chapters, or these lectures, became the 13 chapters in a book of mine which appeared in about, I guess, 75 after some delays as Alternate Worlds, the illustrated history of science fiction.

08:27.000 --> 08:41.040
But as one consequence of its publication, I got a call one day from an editor at New American Library who was admiring it and asked me if I'd like to do a book for them.

08:41.800 --> 09:05.240
And I knew also that I really felt the need for anthologies which covered more than the brief span of the 20s to the 60s, which most anthologies did, and there really wasn't much in the 20s or 30s, most of it,

09:05.240 --> 09:08.600
but it appeared, covered the period of the 40s to the 50s.

09:09.320 --> 09:17.820
So I said yes, and I sent them a proposal for the first volume of the Road to Science Fiction.

09:17.980 --> 09:33.980
At that time, all we knew that there would be would be one volume which covered the period from the earliest prehistory of literature, not to mention science fiction,

09:33.980 --> 09:42.760
up to 1900, and the H.G. Wells' early stories and novels.

09:44.400 --> 09:57.000
The volume used a unique and valuable approach to science fiction criticism. It was an anthology of stories, but each story was accompanied by an essay which covered the story's importance and also discussed the period of science fiction history to which it belonged.

09:57.420 --> 09:59.720
Gunn explains how that volume led to others.

10:00.320 --> 10:13.820
By the time I got finished with the manuscript, I had felt that it really, unlike most books, came out even better than I thought it was going to, and I proposed that we go ahead with a second and third volume.

10:13.820 --> 10:38.140
They said, let's wait and see how this does, and eventually after it had done better than they thought, they agreed that I could go on to volume two and three, which covered the period from 1900 to approximately 1940,

10:38.900 --> 10:46.720
and then from 1940 to 1970 or 1970, actually, the latest one, 76, I think.

10:47.600 --> 10:57.160
Gunn has recently published a fourth volume in the series and says that it's now finished. The title for the entire series is the Road to Science Fiction, and it stands as a major work of science fiction criticism.

10:57.660 --> 11:00.300
