This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

12:38.800 --> 12:45.120
James Gunn is noted not only as an author of science fiction, but as a critic of the field and as a chronicler in the story of its development.

12:45.460 --> 12:57.240
Gunn has recently completed the last volume in his four volume series, The Road to Science Fiction. In this unique work, he traces the development of science fiction from the very beginning of recorded literature until the present day.

12:57.240 --> 13:06.560
What's different and valuable about Gunn's approach in The Road to Science Fiction is that he uses the actual literature itself, from tales belonging to the ancient world and modern short stories.

13:06.860 --> 13:14.200
But each literary selection is accompanied by an essay which discusses the work's importance and deals with the historical period to which it belongs.

13:14.740 --> 13:22.580
When using the volumes then, a reader not only is getting some good science fiction, but he's picking up an education relating to the definition and development of science fiction.

13:22.580 --> 13:28.060
Except for the last one, each volume is also organized around a particular thesis or point.

13:28.640 --> 13:35.320
The first one, for instance, develops the idea that before real science fiction could exist, mankind had to recognize the concept of change.

13:36.180 --> 13:43.080
It seems to me that the essential nature of science fiction is that it deals with change.

13:43.080 --> 13:58.480
In fact, in order for us to recognize a story or a novel as being science fiction, we have to identify that part of it which is different from here and now, our everyday world.

14:00.280 --> 14:07.460
And so it deals with how people would react in changed circumstances.

14:09.500 --> 14:21.680
So, up to approximately the time of the Industrial Revolution, the very concept of change itself was alien to human minds.

14:21.680 --> 14:45.940
It seems to me, looking back over the history of humanity, that mostly people saw change as being only the eternal circle of the seasons changing from spring to summer to fall to winter and back again.

14:45.940 --> 15:03.800
And it wasn't until the Industrial Revolution and, of course, the scientific perceptions that preceded it and accompanied it, which began to create change that people saw could be beneficial.

15:05.380 --> 15:10.200
And in which they could, over which they might be able to exercise some control.

15:10.440 --> 15:23.860
That is, it was man-made change created by human desires and intelligence, and it could be controlled by humanity's exercise of intelligence.

15:23.860 --> 15:32.760
And it seems to me that science fiction was the literary response to that recognition.

15:33.840 --> 15:38.840
The next two volumes develop other ideas that Dunne believes are essential to the development of science fiction.

15:39.360 --> 15:44.380
The notion, for instance, that mankind is a species rather than isolated tribes or nations or races.

15:44.680 --> 15:52.280
But the last volume is a bit different. This is because it deals with the most recent science fiction stories, and it's more difficult to tell which ones will be important.

15:52.280 --> 15:57.300
In the more current story, this is much more difficult to determine.

15:58.260 --> 16:12.440
You can't really say what stories are important until much after they've been published, and you can't certainly say which are typical until you decide what the period really stands for.

16:12.440 --> 16:24.200
So what I did in the fourth volume was to select stories that I thought dealt with the literary uses of science fiction.

16:25.140 --> 16:33.820
And so that volume is primarily concerned not with questions of generic importance, but the question of literary uses.

16:34.620 --> 16:39.820
Dunne has performed a valuable service to the field with the four volumes in his The Road to Science Fiction series.

16:39.820 --> 16:50.420
By defining science fiction, by demonstrating what makes it different from other types of literature, and by revealing its origins, he's made science fiction more understandable and more respectable.

16:51.080 --> 16:53.180
Next time we'll talk with Dunne about his own fiction.

