18:32.500 --> 18:36.860
In much of his science fiction, James Gunn examines the question of what makes man happy.

18:37.520 --> 18:44.080
He extrapolates a future which seems plausible from current social conditions and asks the standard science fiction question, what if?

18:44.080 --> 18:54.200
In his 1963 novel The Joymakers, he fills out the question by asking what if man discovered a drug that would make him perfectly happy, even though it would remove him from the real world.

18:54.900 --> 19:01.440
Gunn answers the question by saying that man would probably accept the opportunity, and then he shows what what happened to man in society as a result.

19:02.520 --> 19:25.220
Ultimately, as it worked out in the novel, it turned out that the people who wanted happiness to get what they want, since what one can get in the external world is limited by the number of people and the number of people who want this particular thing,

19:26.180 --> 19:34.020
ultimately they get what they want by being fed illusions that they get what they want.

19:34.680 --> 19:46.580
And ultimately everybody ends up floating in amniotic cells living on on dreams of success and accomplishment fed by a machine,

19:46.580 --> 19:53.660
which I eventually worked out to be that you're happy when you don't want anything anymore.

19:54.580 --> 20:08.340
And it occurred to me that that is the same as death and ultimately the equation for that is that happiness equals death and that life is still wanting something.

20:09.320 --> 20:19.620
One of Gunn's more recent books, The Dreamers, also published in paperback as The Mind Master, also presents a society in which man has presumably achieved perfect happiness.

20:20.260 --> 20:29.560
And he does so through chemical memory. Any possible experience can be felt by an individual if he is injected with the DNA or RNA of someone who has actually undergone that experience.

20:29.560 --> 20:50.780
It is a comment on the fact that dreaming itself is a non-survival characteristic. It may be the most satisfying experience, but as perhaps I said in The Joymakers,

20:50.780 --> 21:11.760
is perhaps repeated here in a different way, that ultimate satisfaction or dreaming is a death activity and that survival demands something less than total satisfaction.

21:12.640 --> 21:21.580
Both The Joymakers and The Dreamers, along with many of Gunn's other books, consist of a series of related novellas, rather than being a straightforward novel.

21:22.240 --> 21:27.840
Gunn says that he started this practice years ago, not long after he began writing science fiction for a couple of reasons.

21:28.160 --> 21:35.680
It allowed him to be paid twice, since he could publish each novella separately in a magazine before putting it with other novellas to make up a whole novel.

21:36.680 --> 21:49.920
And as a consequence, I have since that time mostly written by novels in the form of publishable fragments or individual stories.

21:49.920 --> 22:07.640
And in a way, I think it's worked rather well because in The Joymakers, I was able to use as a framework, as a subject matter, really an idea rather than a person or a group of people.

22:08.180 --> 22:17.220
And so this novel, which extended over about 200 years, picked up several different people, but basically was about one thing, the science of happiness.

22:17.220 --> 22:26.660
And similarly, the immortals, which also continued for about 200 years, and the listeners, which took a cover to about 150 years.

22:30.040 --> 22:38.180
And all of these seemed to me to focus on an idea, which is what science fiction mostly does.

22:39.080 --> 22:41.520
We'll continue with the work of James Gunn next time.

