24:23.680 --> 24:29.360
The Science Fiction of James Gunn is based on strong, clear ideas that are developed in stories with a good deal of action in them.

24:29.620 --> 24:36.200
One of his better-known books, a 1962 novel entitled The Immortals, is based on a classic science fiction premise.

24:36.760 --> 24:41.160
What if immortality were possible? What would it do to society and to human nature?

24:41.160 --> 24:50.200
The novel focuses on Marshall Cartwright, who is immortal, and a search forum by Leroy Weaver, a dying millionaire who wants Cartwright's blood so that he himself can be immortal.

24:50.900 --> 24:53.140
But the novel is more than a chase or a search.

24:54.360 --> 25:07.380
Certainly, the notion of the search for the immortal, the person that I call Cartwright, Marshall Cartwright, was in there to provide a core of interest.

25:07.380 --> 25:29.340
But I was primarily interested in the novel on the impact of the possibility of immortality on society itself, and interested in dealing with those kinds of impulses that people have relating to immortality and longevity.

25:30.340 --> 25:35.040
By examining people's reactions to immortality, Gunn hopes to make a point about human nature.

25:35.040 --> 25:51.840
And in a certain sense, the immortals embodies as well as anything else that I've written, my basic philosophical position in my work that can be traced through almost all of it.

25:51.840 --> 25:57.100
I suspect that there are no real villains in life.

25:58.560 --> 26:09.800
There are only people who want the same things everybody else wants, but who are willing to do to get them things that other people are not willing to do.

26:09.800 --> 26:19.440
And that the best things in life can be wanted too much.

26:19.900 --> 26:26.220
That if anything that is considered good can be an evil.

26:26.520 --> 26:38.220
And I suppose one of the basic concepts with which I began the immortals was the concept that everybody thinks that it would be wonderful to live forever.

26:38.220 --> 26:52.400
But what if you had a man who accidentally could live forever, but who also whose blood could rejuvenate other people, and his life would be made miserable?

26:52.400 --> 27:21.480
And from there, of course, the entire extrapolation about the ways in which society, knowing the possibility of immortality, would force people with force, society, to pour more and more and more money into medicine until the law of diminishing returns.

27:21.480 --> 27:33.140
And that would mean that half of the world would be devoted to medicine and everybody else would be starving in the swamp.

27:34.040 --> 27:49.200
Gun does indeed show the negative effects of immortality. He suggests that his pursuit would cause great social inequality, cause medical costs to rise drastically, and would also create a society so obsessed with seeking to live forever that it would forget to live for now.

27:49.920 --> 27:54.580
In 1969, there was a television series based on the immortals. We asked Gunn what he thought of it.

27:55.400 --> 28:07.840
Well, I thought it was a total disaster, and that's not uncommon, of course, but the resemblances between the novel and the book are very slight.

28:07.840 --> 28:20.980
My book starts with the immortal being a drifter who comes in and sells a pint of blood and then disappears for the rest of the novel until the very end.

28:23.380 --> 28:40.640
And the television series is all about the immortal and his being pursued, and eventually it turns into simply another search for the papers, another fugitive. Somebody is being chased, but it makes no real difference why he's being chased.

